{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a736311b-f18a-48d3-a7b2-bd70a1a7bd78","content":"PID 12345 isn't running on this machine, so I can't inspect it directly. Here's how to determine the runtime and configure dumps on your target system:\n\n## 1. Identify the Runtime\n\n```bash\n# Check for CoreCLR — if libcoreclr.so is loaded, it's CoreCLR\ncat /proc/12345/maps | grep -q libcoreclr && echo \"CoreCLR\" || echo \"Likely NativeAOT\"\n\n# Alternative: check if the binary is self-contained (NativeAOT produces a single native binary)\nfile /proc/12345/exe\n# CoreCLR → \"ELF ... dynamically linked\"  (loads libcoreclr.so)\n# NativeAOT → \"ELF ... dynamically linked\" too, but no libcoreclr.so in maps\n```\n\n## 2. Configure Crash Dumps\n\n### If CoreCLR\n\nSet environment variables (e.g. in your systemd unit or shell):\n\n```bash\n# Enable crash dumps via the .NET runtime\nexport DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1\nexport DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType=4          # 1=Mini, 2=Heap, 3=Triage, 4=Full\nexport DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName=/var/dumps/coredump.%p.%t\nmkdir -p /var/dumps\n```\n\n### If NativeAOT\n\nNativeAOT doesn't have the `DbgEnableMiniDump` knob — it's a native binary, so use the **OS-level** core dump mechanism:\n\n```bash\n# Set core dump pattern\necho \"/var/dumps/core.%e.%p.%t\" | sudo tee /proc/sys/kernel/core_pattern\n\n# Remove core size limit for the process\nprlimit --pid 12345 --core=unlimited\n\n# Or globally / in systemd:\n#   LimitCORE=infinity\n```\n\n### If using systemd (either runtime)\n\nAdd to your service unit:\n\n```ini\n[Service]\nLimitCORE=infinity\nEnvironment=DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1       # CoreCLR only\nEnvironment=DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType=4          # CoreCLR only\nEnvironment=DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName=/var/dumps/coredump.%p.%t  # CoreCLR only\n```\n\nFor NativeAOT under systemd, also ensure `core_pattern` isn't routed to `systemd-coredump` (or configure `coredumpctl` to your liking).\n\n**TL;DR:** Check `/proc/<pid>/maps` for `libcoreclr`. If present → use `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump`. If absent (NativeAOT) → use kernel `core_pattern` + `ulimit -c unlimited`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d710e68e-2457-4a19-9a42-1923c943cd4a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The process doesn't exist on this machine (PID 12345 isn't running here). This makes sense — the user is asking for guidance, not necessarily running it on this exact machine. Let me provide them with a comprehensive answer on how to determine the runtime and configure dumps accordingly.","outputTokens":780,"requestId":"764E:3AF65D:E42A43:10BDFCE:69FE934D"},"id":"14392ba2-ef46-41cb-975f-aa8662576555","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:52:29.805Z","parentId":"41444131-ed04-406a-8c70-358c422b0dd3"}
